---
// about.astro — the "start here / how to use this site" page.
//
// Wrapped in ChapterLayout so it reads as one book with the rest of the site
// (warm ivory column, sidebar, skip-link, progress bar). It is fully
// SERVER-RENDERED and reads completely with JavaScript disabled: every word
// here is static HTML. The only <script> is a progressive-enhancement wire for
// the "?" help hint (dispatches the same z2r:help-open event the HelpOverlay
// island listens for); strip it and the hint is still legible text.
//
// COPY. This page's prose is FINAL (author-owned, voice-checked against the
// ch1.1/ch1.6 exemplars). The intro is the pitch; the rest is structural /
// instructional text describing how the features actually work.
//
// Links are DERIVED from the real curriculum (discoverChapters), never
// hand-typed, so they can never point at a chapter that does not exist.
import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import Newsletter from "../components/landing/Newsletter.astro";
import { discoverChapters } from "../lib/curriculum.ts";
import "../components/about.css";

const chapters = discoverChapters();
const first = chapters[0] ?? null;
const flagship = chapters.find((c) => c.demo === "pusht_bc_recovery") ?? null;

const startHref = first ? `/${first.slug}/` : "#how";
const flagshipHref = flagship ? `/${flagship.slug}/` : startHref;

// The clone URL is the public GitHub repo; the sample run command is DERIVED
// from a real chapter's artifact (the flagship BC chapter, else the first
// chapter) so the command shown can never drift from a file that exists.
const CLONE_URL = "https://github.com/kaushikb11/zero2robot";
const sampleChapter = flagship ?? first;
const sampleCmd = sampleChapter
  ? `python ${sampleChapter.artifactPath} --seed 0`
  : "python curriculum/phase1_imitation/ch1.1_bc/bc.py --seed 0";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Start here: zero2robot">
  <div class="bk-titleblock ab-wrap">
    <p class="bk-kicker">Start here</p>
    <h1 class="bk-title">
      How to use zero2robot
      <span class="bk-title-sub">read like a book, run like a lab</span>
    </h1>
  </div>

  <div class="ab-wrap">
    <section class="ab-intro" aria-label="What zero2robot is">
      <p>
        zero2robot is an embodied-AI course where <strong>the code is the
        product</strong>. Every chapter is one small, real, readable file you can
        run, from a bare simulation loop to a policy you train, export, and drive
        in your browser. No black boxes, no framework to excavate.
      </p>
      <p>
        You read a chapter like a textbook, then run exactly what you read. The
        browser demos are the same code you train locally; every number carries
        its own provenance; and everything on the learner path finishes on a free
        Colab T4 or a CPU laptop. Forty-three chapters are built and readable
        today, from foundations through the imitation and RL spines, then
        post-training that makes a trained policy reliable, to a from-scratch
        practitioner's stack and a real-arm graduation, with a from-scratch
        physics engine waiting off the main line as optional Depth.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <article class="bk-prose ab-wrap">
    <h2 id="run">Getting started: run the code</h2>
    <p>
      Everything here is a real file you run. There are two ways to do it, and
      every chapter page links to both from its "run this chapter" block.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>In your browser, zero install.</strong> Each chapter has an
      <em>Open in Colab</em> button that opens that chapter's notebook on a free
      Colab T4, no local setup, nothing beyond a Google login. It runs the exact
      code the page shows you.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>On your own machine.</strong> Clone the public repository once, sync
      the pinned environment, and run any chapter's file directly:
    </p>
    <pre class="ab-setup"><code>git clone {CLONE_URL}.git
cd zero2robot
uv sync

# then run any chapter — e.g. behavior cloning from ch1.1:
{sampleCmd}</code></pre>
    <p>
      Every artifact accepts <span class="ab-kbd">--seed</span> (mandatory, so
      runs are reproducible), <span class="ab-kbd">--smoke</span> (a fast smoke
      run to prove the loop before you commit real time), and
      <span class="ab-kbd">--out</span> for where artifacts land. Everything on the
      learner path finishes on that free Colab T4 or a CPU laptop. Anything that
      needs more is marked as an optional Scale Lab.
    </p>

    <h2 id="how">How to read a chapter</h2>
    <p>
      Each chapter page is laid out the same way, top to bottom, so you always
      know where you are. Read it in order the first time through:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>See it work.</strong> A live concept-toy at the top shows the one
        idea the chapter is about: running the real policy or simulation in your
        browser. It is interactive when JavaScript is on and falls back to a
        labelled still poster when it is off, so the point survives either way.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Objectives.</strong> A short "by the end you can…" plate states
        exactly what you will be able to do. Come back and check yourself against
        it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The reading.</strong> The prose column, with the actual code shown
        in dark panels beside it. Those panels are <em>included by region</em>
        straight from the chapter's runnable file, never pasted, and each carries
        the sha256 fingerprint CI re-checks, so what you read is provably what runs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Run it.</strong> An honest wall-clock ledger tells you how long the
        chapter takes on each compute tier. Every time shown is measured, never
        estimated; tiers nobody has measured yet say so plainly.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Practice.</strong> Candidate exercises to work locally. Nothing is
        auto-graded here and nothing phones home. Each exercise gives you a local
        run command to check yourself.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Predict, then run</h2>
    <p>
      Some exercises are <em>predict-then-run</em>. Pick the outcome you expect and
      commit your prediction first. The measured answer and the run command stay
      hidden until you do, because predicting after you already know the answer
      teaches nothing. Your committed prediction is the one signal the site
      records toward progress.
    </p>

    <h2>Concept toys, by hand and by key</h2>
    <p>
      The "See it work" toy exposes exactly one control so you can build intuition
      by poking at it. You can drive every toy from the keyboard, not just the
      pointer: focus the toy (Tab to it, or click it) and use the arrow keys.
      In the flagship covariate-shift toy, for example, the arrow keys nudge the
      block, <span class="ab-kbd">R</span> resets it, and
      <span class="ab-kbd">O</span> sends it out of the region the demonstrations
      covered, the same "aha" you get by dragging. Screen-reader users get the
      same in-distribution / out-of-distribution transition announced live.
    </p>

    <h2>Progress, search, and help</h2>
    <p>
      Your progress lives only in your browser, no account, ever. Reading a
      chapter marks it read (a ✓ appears next to it in the sidebar), committing a
      prediction counts toward completion, and the landing page shows an overall
      and per-phase dashboard with a "continue where you left off" link. Clear your
      browser storage and it resets; it is never sent anywhere.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two keyboard shortcuts are worth learning now:
    </p>
    <table class="ab-keys">
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">Key</th><th scope="col">Does</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="ab-kbd">/</span> or <span class="ab-kbd">⌘</span> <span class="ab-kbd">K</span></td>
          <td>Open search: jump to any chapter, heading, objective, or code region.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="ab-kbd">?</span></td>
          <td>Open the keyboard-shortcuts &amp; how-to overlay from anywhere.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="ab-kbd">Esc</span></td>
          <td>Close whichever overlay is open.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <button type="button" class="ab-help-hint" data-help-open>
      <span class="ab-kbd">?</span>
      <span>Open the full shortcuts &amp; how-to overlay</span>
    </button>

    <h2>The honest constraints</h2>
    <p>
      Two things are true and stated plainly rather than hidden. First, every number
      you read is <strong>measured, not estimated</strong>: each figure traces to a
      recorded run, and where a measurement is still pending (some laptop wall-clock
      times) the page says so rather than guessing. Second, everything on the learner path is built
      to the <strong>free-tier floor</strong>: it completes on a free Colab T4 or a
      CPU laptop. Anything that needs more is marked as an optional Scale Lab, never
      slipped onto the required path.
    </p>

    <div class="ab-cta">
      <a class="ab-btn ab-btn--primary" href={startHref}>
        Start from the first page
        {first && <span class="ab-btn__sub">{first.number} · {first.artifactBasename}</span>}
      </a>
      {flagship && (
        <a class="ab-btn" href={flagshipHref}>Jump to the flagship chapter →</a>
      )}
    </div>

    <section class="ab-support" aria-label="About the author and support">
      <p>Built by <strong>Kaushik Bokka</strong>, AI Research Engineer (<a href="https://x.com/kaushik_bokka" target="_blank" rel="noopener">X</a>, <a href="https://github.com/kaushikb11" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kaushikbokka/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>, <a href="https://huggingface.co/kaushikb11" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hugging Face</a>, <a href="https://kaushikbokka.medium.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Blog</a>). zero2robot is free and open, and always will be. If it helped you, you can <a href="https://www.buymeacoffee.com/kaushikb11" target="_blank" rel="noopener">buy me a coffee</a>.</p>
      <p>Want the ideas as they land? Follow along by email (a weekly note on how Physical AI gets built):</p>
      <Newsletter variant="inline" idPrefix="about" />
    </section>
  </article>

  {/* Progressive enhancement ONLY: wire the "?" hint to open the HelpOverlay
      island (dispatches the event it listens for, regardless of hydration
      order). With JS off the hint is still legible documentation. */}
  <script>
    for (const b of document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>("[data-help-open]")) {
      b.addEventListener("click", () => window.dispatchEvent(new Event("z2r:help-open")));
    }
  </script>

  <style>
    /* The setup block on #run — a dark code panel matching the chapter code
       panels, using the shared design tokens (no palette of its own). Its
       contents scroll horizontally rather than forcing the page to. */
    .ab-setup {
      max-width: var(--measure);
      margin: 0.4rem 0 1.4rem;
      padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
      background: var(--panel, var(--paper-2));
      border: 1px solid var(--rule-strong);
      border-left: 3px solid var(--book-soft);
      border-radius: 3px;
    }
    .ab-setup code {
      display: block;
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      line-height: 1.7;
      color: var(--ink);
      white-space: pre;
    }
    /* A quiet support note, set off by a hairline rule. Unobtrusive by design. */
    /* A quiet one-line author byline and support note, set off by a hairline rule. */
    .ab-support {
      max-width: var(--measure);
      margin-top: 2.2rem;
      padding-top: 1.2rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      color: var(--ink-soft, var(--ink));
    }
    .ab-support a { white-space: nowrap; }
  </style>
</ChapterLayout>
